      "detail": "Leading-edge fabs are designed for multi-decade operational lifespans. EUV tool development programs span decades from concept to production. The infrastructure-life commitment creates strategic stability but limits adaptation. Long-tenor commitments reflect the physical-infrastructure nature of semiconductor manufacturing."
    },
    "Revenue Dependency": {
      "value": "Core business",
      "memo": "Advanced fabrication and EUV lithography are the core businesses of TSMC and ASML respectively, constituting their entire strategic identity.",
      "detail": "TSMC's entire business is contract chip fabrication. ASML's entire business is lithography equipment manufacturing. Core-business dependency means these companies cannot pivot away from semiconductor manufacturing. The strategic chokepoint is inseparable from their corporate identity."
    },
    "Switching Cost": {
      "value": "Captive",
      "memo": "Chip designers are effectively captive to TSMC for leading-edge fabrication: no alternative exists within the relevant capability range.",
      "detail": "Moving a chip design from TSMC to another foundry requires complete redesign for different process characteristics. No alternative foundry offers comparable process capability at TSMC's leading edge. The captive dynamic is absolute rather than merely expensive. Captivity at the foundry level compounds captivity at the GPU and AI layers above."
    },
    "Exit": {
      "value": "Capability entangled",
      "memo": "Exit from TSMC dependency is capability-entangled: chip designs are optimized for specific process nodes and cannot be trivially ported.",
      "detail": "Chip designs incorporate process-specific characteristics that do not transfer to alternative foundries. Years of co-optimization between chip designers and TSMC process engineers create deep entanglement. Alternative foundry qualification would take years and billions of dollars. Capability entanglement at the fabrication layer cascades upward through the entire AI stack."
    },
    "Acceptance Basis": {
      "value": "Market-validated",
      "memo": "Foundry and lithography dominance validates through manufacturing yield, output volume, and the absence of viable alternatives.",
      "detail": "TSMC's position is validated by the fact that every leading AI chip depends on its fabrication capability. ASML's EUV monopoly validates through the physical impossibility of alternative lithography at scale. Yield rates and production volumes serve as the acceptance metrics. The absence of substitutes makes market validation tautological: the market has no other option."
    }
  }
}
